<div id="review_1267124070" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1267124070" />
    <a title="Jessie (Zombie_likes_cake)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake"><img alt="Jessie (Zombie_likes_cake)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1285002362p2/3577389.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1267124070?book_show_action=true">Nov 11, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessie (Zombie_likes_cake)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessie (Zombie_likes_cake)" href="/user/show/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake">Jessie (Zombie_likes_cake)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780571234929" href="/book/show/933790.Sulphuric_Acid">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake?shelf=singles">singles</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake?shelf=no-future">no-future</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake?shelf=read-around-the-world">read-around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake?shelf=french-lit">french-lit</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3577389-jessie-zombie-likes-cake?shelf=read-in-2021">read-in-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1267124070" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1139832592506003082">I really thought I would have a ton to say after finishing &quot;Sulphuric Acid&quot;, on my TBR for years, I was on the lookout for a copy and finally purchased one, I looked forward to it. Now I am not sure I what to tell you, the commentary is spot on for the most part and I think it is an interesting read. It just didn&apos;t hit me as much as I thought it would, it didn&apos;t create the thought turmoil in me as I thought it would.<br/><br/>After all it is about a future where we as a society are so bored by our lives a</span>
  <span id="freeText1139832592506003082" style="display:none">I really thought I would have a ton to say after finishing "Sulphuric Acid", on my TBR for years, I was on the lookout for a copy and finally purchased one, I looked forward to it. Now I am not sure I what to tell you, the commentary is spot on for the most part and I think it is an interesting read. It just didn't hit me as much as I thought it would, it didn't create the thought turmoil in me as I thought it would.<br /><br />After all it is about a future where we as a society are so bored by our lives and our entertainment options that we decide to take it up a notch and have a reality TV show which depicts people in a concentration camp, torturous working conditions, brutal guards, executions and all that jazz. Naturally, it's a huge hit and this book is ultimately a big punch at our TV and to further extent News culture and consumption, the criticism is fairly obvious and I would say well delivered. It even goes further and really zones in on our obsession and simultaneous condemnation of the beauty of celebrities and the idea that that is what makes them great. There is also the role the audience plays, the media plays, the government plays: the triumvirate of consumer culture. How everyone condemns the show (aka TV) but watches nonetheless, and if given the chance takes it a step further without thinking twice. That is powerful and true stuff, something we have all been involved with and carry some guilt. <br />Still, this novella underwhelmed me a bit. I think it was too message driven and for me could have used a bit more plot, with that I think the intensity of this would have been lightened and given some room for thought. As it is I think it is so heavy on its musings and philosophical ponderings it doesn't give you room for your own thoughts. And while it is fair enough that a story like this shouldn't be fun to read, yet it also was a bit of a slog to get through.<br /><br />Good commentary, fantastically evil concept, so so reading experience. And what was that ending? I mean if I could have placed one bet on what happens in this book, I would have said that it for sure will not end well. And then it sort of does? I was honestly confused and, yes, disappointed with that turn. The whole book felt very clear on what it's aiming at but with the conclusion I am a bit baffled. Maybe Nothomb wanted some hope in her nihilistic story, maybe I am just missing what she is saying there.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1139832592506003082" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


