    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2703878495" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2703878495" />
    <a title="Hannah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57072719-hannah"><img alt="Hannah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1546704164p2/57072719.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2703878495?book_show_action=true">Apr 28, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Hannah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Hannah" href="/user/show/57072719-hannah">Hannah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780571234936" href="/book/show/2369928.Sulphuric_Acid">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/57072719-hannah?shelf=owned-to-read">owned-to-read</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2703878495" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3402923705214078745">Amélie Nothomb’s ‘Sulphuric Acid’ had such a promising premise which as soon as I heard I knew I had to get my hands on this short story. As morbid as it may seem, reading about a modern day reality death camp is right up my street. <br/><br/>The 2 stars indicate one for the strong premise and two for the occasions where I found Nothomb’s writing rather beautiful.<br/><br/>Upon starting the book my immediate thoughts were along the lines of “this isn’t what I was expecting” but I carried on nonetheless. However, th</span>
  <span id="freeText3402923705214078745" style="display:none">Amélie Nothomb’s ‘Sulphuric Acid’ had such a promising premise which as soon as I heard I knew I had to get my hands on this short story. As morbid as it may seem, reading about a modern day reality death camp is right up my street. <br /><br />The 2 stars indicate one for the strong premise and two for the occasions where I found Nothomb’s writing rather beautiful.<br /><br />Upon starting the book my immediate thoughts were along the lines of “this isn’t what I was expecting” but I carried on nonetheless. However, this theme continued for me throughout and left me feeling underwhelmed right until the very end. <br /><br />In my opinion, ‘Sulphuric Acid’ did not allow us to feel any sort of emotion for any of the characters despite their circumstances as prisoners or guards. Even Pannonique, the main protagonist seemed bland to me despite all the positive descriptions and praise she seems to receive. The quote “She really thinks she’s something” springs to mind. <br /><br />The most irritating thing for me though was that the whole book just seemed sooooo shallow! I mean, cancelling the whole barbaric show and freeing the prisoners just because the girl deemed “beautiful” might die? Why was it ok for all the other “plain” or “normal” people to die but not her? I know it is just fiction at the end of the day but I really hate reading about this kind of thing and had I known that this was the way ‘Sulphuric Acid’ was going to go, I would not have picked it up.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3402923705214078745" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

