<div id="review_2122886963" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2122886963" />
    <a title="Amy Alice" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5161060-amy-alice"><img alt="Amy Alice" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1357142525p2/5161060.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2122886963?book_show_action=true">Sep 14, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amy Alice" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amy Alice" href="/user/show/5161060-amy-alice">Amy Alice</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780571234929" href="/book/show/933790.Sulphuric_Acid">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5161060-amy-alice?shelf=2017">2017</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2122886963" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8179329687672486431">Fiction, translated from French (Belgian author). <br/>I love Amelie Nothomb. I picked up a load of her stories in France, in English and in French as they are so lovely, and also short which is excellent when you&apos;re trying to read in another language. <br/>This book is a dystopian tale where reality TV has moved to the darkest level - watching an actual death camp. <br/>It has one of the most amazing first pages I have ever read for a book, starting off with: &quot;The time came when the suffering of others was no</span>
  <span id="freeText8179329687672486431" style="display:none">Fiction, translated from French (Belgian author). <br />I love Amelie Nothomb. I picked up a load of her stories in France, in English and in French as they are so lovely, and also short which is excellent when you're trying to read in another language. <br />This book is a dystopian tale where reality TV has moved to the darkest level - watching an actual death camp. <br />It has one of the most amazing first pages I have ever read for a book, starting off with: "The time came when the suffering of others was not enough for them; they needed the spectacle of it, too."<br />Victims are plucked for no reason and everything is filmed. The guards are given free reign to beat the prisoners, and then ultimately to pick which ones will die. One of the prisoners has captured the nation, and the eye of one of the guards. <br />The novel questions whether the people who commit terrible acts are actually any worse than people who sit back and watch. There is a terrible paradox where the enamoured prisoner asks the viewers to stop watching - which makes the program even more watchable. <br />I just loved everything about it, and I especially loved that there was a strong female lead who was obsessed over, like an object, who refused to be objectified, or give up on her morals. It was just excellent and terrifying and will probably be the type of thing that Channel 4 should never read about...</span>
  <a data-text-id="8179329687672486431" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


